Thanissaro Bhikkhu always uses stress, and I like to stick with that.
He says he uses it for three reasons.  The first is  that if you ask
certain people if they are suffering they will say. &quot;Nope!  I have no
suffering.&quot;  but if you ask them if they have any stress they
immediately reply, &quot;oh yes, of course I do.&quot;

The second is that stress even applies to the jhanas.  Once you've
maintained a jhanic state for awhile you can find that there is still
stress there.  It's hard to call that &quot;suffering.&quot;

The third, and my favorite, is that you can't romantacize stress.  You
can romanticize suffering as in &quot;My noble suffering.&quot;  Saying that you
have stress doesn't have that sense of admirable stoicism.  You never
hear about &quot;my noble stress.&quot;

I think the word suffering is better when applied to the &quot;whole
catastrophe&quot; which includes not just oneself but the whole of
humanity.  When I think of &quot;saving all sentient beings&quot; my compassion
is more stirred when I think of suffering than of stress.  There's
obviously a lot of it out there.

